---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Peak-Hour Fleet Distribution at Special Events: Pride Parade Analysis"
  year="2024"
  category="Event Analysis · Mobility Management"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'Pandas', 'QGIS', 'Populus', 'Density Mapping']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Overview</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Tel Aviv's Pride Parade is the city's largest annual street event, drawing hundreds of thousands
        of participants and radically reshaping transportation demand across the central city. In the
        hours surrounding the parade, shared e-scooter demand spikes dramatically — vehicles cluster
        along the route and surrounding streets, while large sections of the city simultaneously lose
        access due to road closures and temporary parking restrictions.
      </p>
      <p>
        This analysis used real-time fleet data from the Populus platform to map where shared
        e-scooters were available and where demand concentrated during the parade's peak hour.
        Fleet distribution maps were overlaid with temporary parking restriction zones issued for the
        event, revealing gaps between where vehicles were parked and where riders needed them.
      </p>
      <p>
        Findings helped operators understand spatial mismatches ahead of future events and supported
        the municipality's pre-positioning negotiations with operators. The density maps also identified
        streets where parking restrictions created effective no-go zones without compensating supply
        in adjacent areas.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Pride Parade Peak Hour</h2>
    <div class="proj-map-grid">
      <div>
        <img
          src={`${base}/maps/pride-distribution.jpg`}
          alt="Map of shared e-scooter distribution during Tel Aviv Pride Parade peak hour"
          class="proj-map"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <p class="proj-map-caption">Vehicle fleet distribution at peak hour — Pride Parade 2024.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <img
          src={`${base}/maps/pride-density.jpg`}
          alt="Density map of shared e-scooter concentration during Pride Parade"
          class="proj-map"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <p class="proj-map-caption">Vehicle density surface during parade peak hour.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methods</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Raw Populus status-change data was filtered to the event's peak-hour window and processed
        into point-in-time vehicle snapshots using Python and Pandas. Vehicle locations were then
        joined to a grid layer and to parking restriction polygons (provided by the municipality as
        GeoJSON) to identify restricted and unrestricted availability zones.
      </p>
      <p>
        Density surfaces were generated using KDE on vehicle coordinates, and trip origin data from
        the same hour provided a demand reference layer. Both layers were visualized in QGIS with
        matched scales and extents to enable direct comparison between supply and demand patterns.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>
